<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yerin Calls For Combined Security Efforts on Crime </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yerin Calls For Combined Security Efforts on Crime </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2705221194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1739 GMT 27 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2705221194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russian Interior Minister Viktor Yerin has 
emphasized that there are no differences between the Interior 
Ministry and the Federal Counterintelligence Service (FCS) as 
represented by some parts of the media. Speaking at a 
nation-wide conference in the FCS in Moscow Friday, he called 
for combined efforts and coordinated activities by the 
law-enforcement bodies in the struggle against crime which had 
corrupted many state offices, the FCS public relations center 
told Interfax. 
  The conference was attended by officials of the Prosecutor's 
Office, State Customs Committee, Supreme Court, tax police and 
border guards. 
  Yerin said that revealing traitors was equally important for 
all agencies. "We struggle for the honor of the law-enforcement 
bodies, removing those who cooperate with criminals," he was 
quoted as saying. 
  In Yerin's opinion, supported by the FCS Director Sergey 
Stepashin, it is necessary to develop an agreement between the 
Interior Ministry and the FCS clearly defining their interaction 
in critical and emergency situation. 
  Acting Prosecutor General Aleksey Ilyushenko said that crime 
had expanded in Russia recently. He called for the return of 
investigation units which used to be the most professional 
structures within the Russian Security Ministry specializing on 
specially grave crimes. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

