<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shakhray Not To Seek Presidential Candidacy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shakhray Not To Seek Presidential Candidacy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2705202394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1857 GMT 27 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2705202394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Igor Belskiy] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 27 TASS -- Russian Vice-Premier Sergey 
Shakhray will not run for president in 1996, according to his 
statement at today's meeting with students and professors of 
Moscow University. 
  Speaking of his resignation from the post of minister for 
affairs of nationalities and the voiced intention to leave the 
vice-premier's post, Shakhray said "the question has been 
closed, I remain the vice-premier". He told the audience that 
meetings with the prime minister and president assured him "his 
potential has not been exhausted". 
  Shakhray did not exclude "the right to future existence of 
Far Eastern or Urals republics on condition it will not be a 
mere isolation of the region or the territory within the current 
administrative borders". In his opinion, this is possible "in 
case of formation of larger federation subjects on the basis of 
inter-regional economic unity and cooperation". 
  Commenting on press reports claiming fake results of the 
December 12 referendum on the new Russian Constitution, the 
vice-premier said "as long as these claims are not proved, I 
will think that the Constitution has been approved". The 
Constitution is a reality, said Shakhray. 

</TEXT>

