<H3> <TI>   LDPR Claims Laws Obstructed by Russia's Choice </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    LDPR Claims Laws Obstructed by Russia's Choice </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK3105085094 Moscow SEGODNYA in Russian, 31 May 94, p 2 </F>
<F P=103> MK3105085094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow SEGODNYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian, </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Anatoliy Veslo report under the "Recipes" rubric: "A </F>
Detailed Reply by the LDPR to Mr. Svanidze. Zhirinovskiy 
Faction's Innovations Run Up Against `Russia's Choice'"] 
  [Text] Vladimir Zhirinovskiy's Liberal Democrats, outraged 
by television journalist Nikolay Svanidze's statements that the 
Liberal Democratic Party of Russia [LDPR] has not submitted a 
single draft to the Duma, told the public about their lawmaking 
activities and their economic research efforts. 
  LDPR deputies explained that all of their innovations run up 
against "Russia's Choice" opposition in the Duma Council and at 
plenary sittings. For this reason the draft laws "On Regulation 
of Ownership in the Russian Federation," "On Russian Federation 
Property Abroad," "On Trust," "On the Restoration of Property 
Rights of Russian Federation Citizens Violated in the Period 17 
March 1917 through 12 December 1993," and "On the Brain Drain 
From the Russian Federation" have not become full-fledged state 
acts after all. 
  The journalists' close attention was drawn to the first 
three 
draft laws. The law "On Trust" was drafted by Deputy Aleksey 
Zuyev, who, before his election, was adviser to the president of 
the "GMM" trust company, whose activities drew complaints from 
the Finance Ministry and the Central Bank. The other two laws 
are devoted to the implementation of the party's economic 
program. The one regulating the rights of ownership puts an end 
to the voucher privatization that is nearly completed anyhow. 
Instead of this robbery, all citizens of the Russian Federation 
are supposed to open Savings Bank accounts marked "NP" (National 
Property), "PP" (Privatized Property), and the "RNP" (Regional 
National Property). The various owners -- the state, the 
regions, and private owners who have snapped up their share of 
the generous LDPR handouts -- are supposed to put their earnings 
in these accounts. It has been decided to name this process 
privatization. That, the Liberal Democratic innovators have 
calculated, would make for a comfortable life for 60 percent of 
Russia's citizens. 
  It is even easier with investments in industry -- one only 
has to mortgage all Russian Federation property abroad in 
Japanese banks, to pour all the earned yen into the needy 
enterprises, to ban without fail liberalization of external 
trade, to stir the concoction and have Mr. Zhirinovskiy and his 
economic advisers drink it up with a feeling of deep gratitude. 
A sudden drain of healthy brains, if the program gets 
implemented, can be prevented by the corresponding law drafted 
in the committee on geopolitics. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-38418 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov104_b_94013" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-104 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  30 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zhirinovskiy: Kaliningrad Inalienable Part of Russia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Zhirinovskiy: Kaliningrad Inalienable Part of Russia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3005170494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1512 GMT 30 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3005170494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Leader of Russia's Liberal-Democratic Party Vladimir 
Zhirinovskiy stated in Moscow on Monday that "sooner or later 
historical justice will triumph and the Vilnius territory which 
was always part of Russia, would be re-joined to Russia and the 
Kaliningrad Region will cease to be isolated from us." 
  He told the press conference devoted to a State Duma 
delegation's visit to Russia's Baltic exclave, located between 
Lithuania and Poland, that "Kaliningrad is an inalienable part 
of Russia and that neither Lithuanians, nor Estonians, nor Poles 
or Germans, will be able to tear it away from the motherland." 
  The Kaliningrad Region (former East Prussia) was joined to 
Russia following the Potsdam conference in 1945. The Vilnius 
territory is the south eastern part of Lithuania which was 
occupied by Poland in 1919-39. In 1939, following the 
occupation of Poland by Germany, the Soviet Union sent its 
troops to this territory and subsequently joined it to Lithuania. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-38419 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov104_b_94014" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-104 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  27 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rutskoy Ready To Lead United Opposition </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rutskoy Ready To Lead United Opposition </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2705220094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1739 GMT 27 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2705220094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The closest political goal of the opposition 
consists in the establishment of a single popular movement which 
would gain the majority of seats in the Russian parliament 
during the next parliamentary elections and thereafter win the 
presidential elections, former Russian vice president Aleksandr 
Rutskoy stated in an interview with Interfax today. 
  The Accord for Russia opposition movement will hold a 
meeting 
of its National Council in Moscow on Saturday. 
  Rutskoy stressed that the opposition should be careful not 
to 
let one more candidate from the present regime to take the 
highest post. That is why the opposition needs a single 
candidate. 
  Rutskoy said that each of the party leaders believed that he 
must be elected the president. Rutskoy himself said that he 
does not especially seek the presidency and that any candidacy 
should be put forward taking into consideration the interests of 
the cause. 
  Rutskoy suggested that a tough politician must take this 
post 
since the present situation in the country required rule with no 
compromise, consensus or games with the law. 
  Rutskoy said nothing would be changed in the country as long 
as Boris Yeltsin remained in power. Neither a government of 
national confidence, nor a new composition of the parliament 
will change the situation. It must go through radical changes, 
Rutskoy affirmed. 
  Rutskoy said he was ready to lead the united opposition. 

</TEXT>

