<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chernomyrdin Claims Crisis Has Reached `Peak' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chernomyrdin Claims Crisis Has Reached `Peak' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3005151594 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1318 
GMT 30 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD3005151594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, 30 May, (BIZNESS-TASS) -- "The possibility 
of a change in the macroeconomic situation in Russia is 
emerging," Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin said today 
in the Russian Federation Government at a meeting of heads of 
administrations. The Constitution itself and a package of 
presidential economic decrees signed last week are the 
legislative preconditions for that. 
  "The crisis has reached its peak", V. Chernomyrdin pointed 
out. Ensuring that the economic situation finally goes in the 
direction of getting better, that is, implementing the reforms 
in the production sphere is what should become the task for the 
government in 1995-1997. But the basis for this has already 
been prepared. This is shown by the figures of the dynamics in 
the rise of production, and the stabilization of the ruble (in 
particular, the steady fall of the inflation rate and a 
reduction in the Central Bank's refinancing interest rates), the 
prime minister said. 
  According to V. Chernomyrdin, the Russian regions have 
always 
been the moving force behind the reforms. That is why today's 
meeting with the heads of administrations was devoted to 
examining such issues as designing measures for the final stage 
of the vouchers' privatization process, discussing the program 
for the privatization of state and municipal enterprises after 1 
July 1994 and the examination of the new Russian Federation Land 
Code. As is known, the heads of oblast and kray administrations 
took part in drawing up these documents together with experts 
from ministries and departments. 

</TEXT>

