<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chernomyrdin Speaks on New Land Code </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chernomyrdin Speaks on New Land Code </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3005220294 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1532 
GMT 30 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD3005220294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [BUSINESS-TASS] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 30 May -- "The adoption of a new land code 
has been necessitated by a discrepancy between current land laws 
and the Russian constitution, as well as a number of 
presidential decrees and government resolutions," according to 
Russian Federation Prime Ministers Viktor Chernomyrdin, speaking 
to the participants in a meeting at the government house. The 
main disadvantage of the 1991 code, i.e. the lack of the concept 
of "land ownership," has been eliminated in the draft of the law 
submitted today for debate by heads of administrations. 
  For the first time a land law stipulates a procedure for 
acquiring land by juridical persons (by transferring land plots 
and parcels of land to enterprises' authorized capital or 
through purchase of land), V. Chernomyrdin said. 
  The draft of the new land code also contains a description 
of 
procedures for land deals by physical persons (buying, selling, 
or mortgage operations), as well as giving or inheriting land. 
It stipulates that owners of inherited land plots can become 
owners if they wish. However, if a land plot is larger than the 
maximum size allowed for a transfer of land ownership free of 
charge, the remaining part may be kept as non-transferable 
inheritance or bought out in credit. 
  In accordance with the current constitution, the draft of 
the 
land code transfers a larger proportion of land regulation 
rights to the constituent parts of the federation, unlike the 
present land law, the prime minister said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

