<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Regional Heads Discuss Second Stage of Privatization </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Regional Heads Discuss Second Stage of Privatization </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3005162494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1517 GMT 30 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3005162494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By BUSINESS-TASS] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 30 TASS -- The programme of privatisation 
of state and municipal enterprises in Russia after July 1, 1994 
was submitted for approval to a conference of regional heads 
held in the building of the Russian Government on Monday. 
  The conference was addressed by chairman of the Russian 
committee for state property, Anatoliy Chubays, who said that 
unlike the first stage of voucher privatisation, during the 
second stage priority will be given to quality standards. 
  The evaluation of property to be privatised after July 1, 
will be made in prices which were in effect as of January 1, 
1994. The market value of a privatised object will differ from 
the starting price by several dozen per cent, rather than by 
several dozen times, Chubays said. 
  The programme of post-voucher privatisation will enable 
local 
authorities to increase the starting cost of property by 70-200 
per cent, depending on conditions of each particular region, 
Chubays said. Privileges granted to work collectives in the 
course of privatisation have underwent substantial changes in 
the new programme. Workers and managers of enterprises who will 
prefer the first variant will be given only 25 per cent of 
privileged shares (while under the programme in effect today, 
workers and managers, including the directors' corps, received 
40 per cent of the athorised stock). 
  A second variant, which is the most popular among privatised 
enterprises, envisages that only 10 per cent of shares will 
given to them on privileged terms (against 51 per cent in effect 
today.) 
  Nevertheless, privatised enterprises will be allowed to 
appropriate 51 percent of all revenues from privatisation, 
Chubays said, adding that this measure will help former 
state-run enterprises overcome the structural crisis as soon as 
possible. 

</TEXT>

