<H3> <TI>   Russian Capital Outflow for 1992-93 Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russian Capital Outflow for 1992-93 Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3105110794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1008 GMT 31 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3105110794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Igor Galkin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 31 TASS -- The outflow of Russian capital 
abroad comprised 10-15 billion US dollars in 1992-1993, 
according to chief banker Viktor Gerashchenko. 
  He told a press conference on Tuesday that a system which is 
going to cut short the export of capital was introduced only 
this year. It will monitor all import and export operations. 
  The chairman of the central bank denied press reports that 
he 
objected to the six economic decrees signed by the president of 
late. He said they would help create a favourable climate for 
reforms, although certain changes in legislation would be 
necessary for that. 
  Gerashchenko added that the president is expected to sign a 
decree lifting certain limitations on the activities of foreign 
banks in Russia. 

</TEXT>

