<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shevardnadze, Russian Commander Meet in Tbilisi </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shevardnadze, Russian Commander Meet in Tbilisi </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2805173294 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1502 
GMT 28 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2805173294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Albert Kochetkov] </F>
  [Text] Tbilisi, 28 May -- Eduard Shevardnadze had 
discussions in Tbilisi today with Lieutenant General Aleksandr 
Sokolov, deputy commander in chief of the emergency land forces 
of the Russian Defence Ministry, about the mechanism for 
introducing and deploying peacekeeping forces in the 
Georgian-Abkhaz conflict zone. 
  Gen. Sokolov visited Abkhazia earlier on the same mission 
and 
is reported to have spent the day before the meeting 
reconnoitering at the Inguri River, the place proposed for the 
deployment of the peacekeeping contingent to disengage the 
warring sides. According to unconfirmed information, about 
3,000 servicemen can be ready to carry out this task within a 
few hours. 
  In accordance with the Georgian-Abkhaz agreements previously 
reached under the aegis of the United Nations and with Russian 
mediation, the peacekeeping forces are also to ensure the 
security of the refugees returning to their previous places of 
residence. Various sources put their number at 250-300,000. 
  Offical sources in Tbilisi are not reporting any details 
about the meeting between Eduard Shevardnadze and are not 
commenting on it. However, to judge from the way events are 
developing, the peacekeeping troops may be introduced into the 
Georgian-Abkhaz conflict zone in the very near future. 

</TEXT>

