<H3> <TI>   Aliyev To Lower Parliament Quorum After Walk-Out </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Aliyev To Lower Parliament Quorum After Walk-Out </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK2705114494 Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA in Russian 27 May 94 
p 3 </F>

<F P=103> MK2705114494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report under the "NEGA Reports" rubric: </F>
"Azerbaijan"] 
  [Text] The Azerbaijani president has not yet signed an 
edict on lowering the quorum in parliament. So, an appeal by 28 
deputies to Geydar Aliyev requesting that the requisite quorum 
at the National Assembly be reduced from 34 to 26 deputies has 
so far gone unanswered; the measure is designed to help 
circumvent the discussion of the Bishkek protocol that has been 
demanded in an ultimatum by a group of the parliament's 
opposition members, who walked out from the previous meeting for 
an indefinite period. 
  KHABAR-SERVICE's correspondent learned this from sources at 
the presidential staff. The news agency also reports that 
although such an edict will be unlawful, Geydar Aliyev is 
inclined to grant the request of the parliamentary majority, and 
the document is expected to be signed in the next few days. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

