<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Ulmanis Returns From U.S. Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    President Ulmanis Returns From U.S. Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2705120394 Riga Radio Riga Network in Latvian 1100 GMT 27 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2705120394 </F>
<F P=104>  Riga Radio Riga Network </F>
<F P=105>  Latvian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] State President Guntis Ulmanis has returned from his 
visit to the United States. At a news conference, Ulmanis said 
that in his talks with U.S. President Bill Clinton and UN 
Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali, they discussed the issue 
of the problems of the Skrunda radar station. Special attention 
was also paid to the Russian Army's Paldiski nuclear center in 
Estonia and the Kaliningrad region as possible flash-points in 
the Baltic region. The UN secretary general agreed that the 
progress of the treaty on the Skrunda radar station must also be 
monitored by this internatonal organization. The state 
president also particularly noted that no one has reproached 
Latvia for not observing human rights, and this problem was not 
discussed. 
  It is possible that in a few years a conference of national 
leaders could be held in Riga on the problems of disarmament and 
the environment. 

</TEXT>

