<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Expert Council Discusses Demographic Scheme </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Expert Council Discusses Demographic Scheme </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3005163494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1520 GMT 30 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3005163494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Lilya Kuznetsova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 30 TASS -- A general demographic scheme 
for Russia's territories, determining the main tendencies for 
the development of the country's urban and rural communities and 
separate regions, stipulating versions for accommodating 
refugees, displaced persons, families of servicemen, migrants 
from the north, and outlining ways to officially regulate those 
processes in conditions of a market economy, was discussed and 
approved today by an expert council under the Russian president. 
  As noted by Aleksandr Krivov, vice-chairman of the Russian 
State Building Committee, the key task, indicated in the 
document, is to draw up a concept and a long-term policy for 
settling people on Russia's vast territories and to elaborate 
concrete proposals for this purpose. 
  The pivotal idea of the general scheme is to elaborate a 
basic settlement pattern and to site and form urban 
conglomerations, constituting the key form of contemporary and 
future distribution of the Russian population. They are to be 
provided with a powerful infrastructure, ensuring modern 
transport and communication services, information facilities, 
and the ecological safety of a given district. 
  The mid-Russian, south Siberia and Pacific regions are 
indicated as the priority settlement areas. Leningrad, Pskov, 
Novgorod, Tver, Yaroslavl, Kostroma and Vologda regions, as well 
as the middle belt of Russia and the Urals, Siberia, and the Far 
East are earmarked for the settlement of refugees from the 
republics of the former Soviet Union, for the families of 
servicemen and resettlers from the north, the number of which is 
expected to reach 5.5-8 million people by the year 2000. 
  A package of federal programmes is to be drawn up on the 
basis of this document, envisaging the development of small and 
medium-size towns, revival of the Russian countryside, revival 
and development of the mid-Russian region, and the accommodation 
of migrants. The expert council moved to "determine the status 
of the general scheme as a regularly amended prognosis-type 
document", to approve the draft's concept, to set up an 
inter-departmental commission for shape Russia's town-building 
policy and to draw up a draft resolution of the Russian 
Government "On the main directions of the state town-building 
and settlement policy in the Russian Federation". 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

