<H3> <TI>   Commission on Irregularities in St Petersburg Elections </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Commission on Irregularities in St Petersburg Elections </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2005194394 Moscow RIA in English 1735 GMT 20 May 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD2005194394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow RIA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, May 20, RIA -- The Central Electoral 
Commission of the Russian Federation today recommended St. 
Petersburg Mayor Anatoliy Sobchak before June 10 to correct the 
violations of the legislation on elections and make the 
necessary amendments in the statute on elections to the St. 
Petersburg City Assembly. 
  This decision follows the fact that when elections were held 
to the City Assembly on March 20 and 21 and also after a repeat 
voting on April 3, 1994 the St. Petersburg mayor violated with 
his orders a number of articles of the basic regulations on 
elections to representative bodies of state authority. 
  Vyacheslav Marychev, a State Duma deputy who was present at 
the session, after saying emotionally that "whole military units 
were forced to vote", demanded that the commission should not 
limit itself to recommendations, but revoke the results of the 
repeated voting. 
  But Aleksandr Ivanchenko, deputy chairman of the Central 
Electoral Commission, explained that only the president has this 
kind of competence. 
  In the event of the St. Petersburg mayor failing to meet the 
commission's recommendations, it can only draw the president's 
attention to Sobchak's actions. 
  The session was also told that the Supreme Court of the 
Russian Federation today left unsatisfied a complaint by the St. 
Petersburg City court that the City Assembly elections were 
unlawful. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

