<H3> <TI>   Adviser on Ukrainian, Crimean `Tempered Bickering' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Adviser on Ukrainian, Crimean `Tempered Bickering' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3105111394 Moscow RIA in English 0831 GMT 31 May 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD3105111394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow RIA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, May 31, RIA -- Keeping the situation calm on 
the surface, the Ukrainian and Crimean Supreme Soviets started 
"tempered bickering," believes Crimean president's advisor for 
military issues Pyotr Chernyatevich. 
  Speaking on the phone with a RIA correspondent he claimed 
that the Ukrainian parliament traces every move taken by their 
Crimean counterparts. Once the Crimean Supreme Soviet has put 
today's plenary session on Constitution off from 9 A.M. to 2 
P.M., the Ukrainian Supreme Soviet fired back and postponed its 
session with a similar agenda from Tuesday to Wednesday. 
  Despite this wait-and-see policy adopted by Ukraine, says 
the 
presidential advisor, there are good reasons to hope that the 
working group of the Ukrainian Supreme Soviet will arrive in the 
Crimea at long last next Thursday. Only then will it be 
possible to bring a definite solution to the long-running 
dispute. 
  In his words, the people in the Crimea keep a watchful eye 
on 
the developments in anticipation of new moves by Kiev. 
  The fact that deputy heads of Ukrainian power ministries are 
still based in the Crimea only increases psychological tension 
on the local population, insists Mr. Chernyatevich. 

</TEXT>

