<DOCNO> FBIS4-38534 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov105_d_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-105 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  31 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   N. Ossetia, Ingush Presidents on State of Emergency </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    N. Ossetia, Ingush Presidents on State of Emergency </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0106001794 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1545 
GMT 31 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0106001794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS parliamentary correspondent Lyudmila Yermakova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 31 May -- Satisfaction with the Federation 
Council's endorsement of the Russian president's decree 
extending the state of emergency in the area of conflict in 
North Ossetia and Ingushetia was expressed in an interview with 
an ITAR-TASS correspondent by the presidents of both republics, 
who are members of the chamber. In the opinion of North 
Ossetian leader Akhsarbek Galazov, the refugee problem can only 
be resolved if people who are to live together understand that 
this is necessary. He also thinks that the refugee problem must 
be tackled throughout Russia. 
  Ingush President Ruslan Aushev said the new decree was 
"better than previous ones, since it was more down-to-earth." 
Specifically, it indicates that the procedure for moving people 
into abandoned dwellings must be submitted by 15 June. "But 
there is one danger: the decree may not be implemented," he 
added. 
  Concern that the decree may not be implemented was also 
voiced by Issa Kustoyev, chairman of the Federation Council's 
committee for constitutional legislation: "the disease has been 
allowed to develop unchecked and over billion rubles allocated 
to settle the problem have been swallowed up, yet there are 
still homeless people, and they are still starving." According 
to him, not a single question has yet been solved, although 
"decree after decree repeats that the provisional administration 
as a special form of rule must control the situation." A deputy 
who had visited the area of the conflict on more than one 
occasion, noted that the deputies' monitoring commission which 
it had been decided to set up had to check to see that the 
provisions of the presidential decree were being implemented. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-38535 </DOCNO>
