<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   North Ossetia Denies Killing Georgians </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    North Ossetia Denies Killing Georgians </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2805213294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1956 GMT 28 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2805213294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Vladimir Shanayev] </F>
  [Text] Vladikavkaz May 28 TASS -- The North Ossetian 
Interior Ministry has denied reports about the participation of 
North Ossetian citizens in the terroristic act that killed eight 
Georgians near the village of Algun on Friday. 
  On Friday media reports said that "the terroristic group Les 
[not further identified] based on the outskirts of the Ossetian 
village of Tarskoye where the state of emergency is in effect 
killed eight Georgians near the Ingush village of Algun who were 
building a road between Ingushetia and Georgia, bypassing North 
Ossetia. They said that the bodies of the builders were 
allegedly transported to the Sunzhensk district of Ingushetia. 
  Information obtained by ITAR-TASS from the press service of 
the North Ossetian Interior Ministry said that the group Les 
does not exist in the republic. The Ingush side made a 
statement about the brutal killing of the Georgian workers 
without preliminary investigation into the circumstances of the 
incident, the press service said. 
  The press service said that the aim of this disinformation 
is 
to "aggravate the situation on the eve of the debates on the 
extension of the state of emergency in parts of North Ossetia 
and Ingushetia, discredit North Ossetian bodies of power, build 
up tension and disrupt the negotiation process initiated by 
North Ossetia." 
  The state of emergency in some districts of North Ossetia 
has 
been extended until May 31. According to reports, the situation 
in these districts remains tense mostly because of the 
continuing fighting and attacks on civilians, military units and 
police patrols and hostage taking. 
  Sporadic shooting broke out seven times in the Prigorod 
District of North Ossetia last night. No casualties were 
reported. The situation is under control of Russian 
peace-keeping troops and local law enforcement bodies. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

