<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Reaffirms Stand on Republics' Sovereignty </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin Reaffirms Stand on Republics' Sovereignty </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3005142894 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1243 
GMT 30 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD3005142894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Tamara Zamyatina, Yuriy Sizov, </F>
and Nikolay Sorokin] 
  [Text] Naberezhnyye Chelny (Republic of Tatarstan), 30 May 
-- Boris Yeltsin does not renounce the formula "take as much 
sovereignty as you can stand," which he uttered in 1991 with 
regard to the republics and regions that were part of Russia. 
The president of the Russian Federation stated on the steps of 
the aircraft on arrival in Naberezhnyye Chelny: "I was beaten, 
severely criticized for this phrase, but I endured it all and 
was right." 
  To confirm his words, Boris Yeltsin gave the example of 
Tatarstan, the bilateral treaty which showed that "the republic 
has taken on as much responsibilities as it can cope with. As 
for what is beyond its capabilities, it has delegated that to 
the federal authorities." 
  According to the Russian president, the main thing for 
Russia 
at present is to implement the treaty. In the view of Emil 
Pain, a Russian president expert, both sides, Russia and 
Tatarstan, have so far been violating the agreement: the 
republic is sending four-five times less tax revenue to the 
federal budget than had been laid down in the agreement. In 
turn, Russia is not ensuring that a mechanism for the 
implementation of the treaty is being drawn up. 
  Tatarstan's President Mintimer Shaymiyev, when greeting 
Boris 
Yeltsin at Naberezhnyye Chelny airport, reaffirmed his adherence 
to the phrase "strong republics -- strong center." He said that 
the aim of the present meeting was "strengthening trust, finding 
a joint solution to economic problems, and discussing federal 
programs." 
  Boris Yeltsin intends to begin his look at the course of 
reform in Tatarstan at the Kama automobile works, beginning with 
the production plant that was hit by fire, to decide what help 
can be given to the automobile manufacturers. In the view of 
Sergey Shakhray, which he expressed to an ITAR-TASS 
correspondent on the eve of the visit to Tatarstan, the matter 
does not concern credits or subsidies for the Kama automobile 
works, but guarantees from the Russian Government for commercial 
and foreign investment in the joint-stock company. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-38538 </DOCNO>
