<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kazakhstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Intends To Pursue Stringent Financial Policy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Intends To Pursue Stringent Financial Policy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3105125994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1102 GMT 31 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3105125994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Government of Kazakhstan intends to firmly 
pursue a stringent financial policy and adhere to the budget 
deficit agreed upon with the International Monetary Fund -- no 
more than 4 percent. Finance Minister Erkeshbai Derbisov said so 
in an interview with INTERFAX after Monday's session of the 
Cabinet of Ministers held to consider changes in Kazakhstan's 
budget for the current year. 
  Earlier the finance minister said that President Nursultan 
Nazarbayev's decision to raise the minimal wages to 100 tenges 
may entail a rise in the budget deficit. 
  According to estimates, in May inflation in Kazakhstan will 
reach 26 percent, Derbisov said. In January it ran at 42 
percent, in February at 27 pct, in March at 17 percent and in 
April at 31 percent. 

</TEXT>

