<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Finnish Offer of Russian Mediation Turned Down </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Finnish Offer of Russian Mediation Turned Down </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3105141994 Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network in Finnish 
1300 GMT 31 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD3105141994 </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Finnish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Sinikka Siekkinen from Tallinn] </F>
  [Text] As expected, the relations between Estonia and 
Russia were a central topic in the talks during the first day of 
President Martti Ahtisaari's visit. Ahtisaari spent most of his 
time today in talks with Lennart Meri, his Estonian colleague. 
According to the Estonian political leadership, some light can 
be discerned in the talks with the Russians, to the extent that 
Estonia believes it will be able to solve the problem of the 
Russian soldiers with Russia bilaterally. 
  This optimism is a consequence of talks with Russian Foreign 
Minister Andrey Kozyrev a few days ago and of the fact that 
Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Vitaliy Churkin is due in 
Estonia next week. According to Lennart Meri, it would now seem 
that a mediator is not needed. Meri has also told this to 
President Ahtisaari. Meri said that Ahtisaari had, however, 
made a beautiful symbolic gesture by telling the Estonians that 
he can always offer the negotiators premises, light, and food, 
if they so wish. But according to Meri, Estonia will return to 
the mediation task after the last day of August at the earliest, 
if the troops of the former Soviet Army have not left Estonia by 
then. 
  Ahtisaari's visit has taken place so far in a warm 
atmosphere. An Estonian daily even wrote that a new Ahtisaari 
era is beginning in Finnish-Estonian relations. 

</TEXT>

