<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   G-7 Fails To Commit to Chernobyl Aid </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    G-7 Fails To Commit to Chernobyl Aid </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3105134394 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1243 
GMT 31 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD3105134394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Viktor Demidenko and Mikhail </F>
Melnik] 
  [Text] Kiev, 31 May (ITAR-TASS) -- The working meeting 
between representatives of the G7 countries and a Ukrainian 
delegation on what is to happen to Chernobyl nuclear power 
station has achieved no concrete results. 
  The international experts did not commit themselves to a 
specific amount of assistance to Ukraine to build new nuclear 
power stations in place of Chernobyl, Deputy Prime Minister 
Valeriy Shmarov told ITAR-TASS in an exclusive interview today. 
"Billions of dollars are needed to carry out the whole package 
of projects. At least four billion is needed to close down 
Chernobyl nuclear power station alone." 
  Valeriy Shmarov said the talks will be continued. He 
described Ukraine's position as follows: "If you want to avert 
danger, help us." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

