<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shevardnadze, CIS Official Discuss Peacekeeping Troops </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shevardnadze, CIS Official Discuss Peacekeeping Troops </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3105191494 Moscow NTV in Russian 1800 GMT 31 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3105191494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NTV </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Video report from Tbilisi by correspondent D. Keliselidze] </F>
  [Text] [Announcer] The introduction of CIS peacekeeping 
forces to the area of the Georgian-Abkhazian conflict may begin 
on 10 June. This has just been announced after a meeting 
between Eduard Shevardnadze and CIS Acting Secretary Korotchenya. 
  [Keliselidze] Today Eduard Shevardnadze had a half-hour 
meeting at Tbilisi airport with Ivan Korotchenya, chairman of 
the CIS acting secretariat. The fact that the meeting took 
place at the airport and that there was no time for the 
traditional Georgian hospitality showed that this visit was 
urgent and concerned important questions. And that's how it was. 
  Russian President Boris Yeltsin, head of the council of the 
CIS states, had appealed to the leaders of CIS countries to 
examine the question of introducing peacekeeping troops into the 
Georgian-Abkhazian conflict zone, as he was asked to by Georgian 
Head of State Eduard Shevardnadze and Abkhazian Supreme Soviet 
Chairman Vladislav Ardzinba. In order to resolve this question 
then according to procedure, it was necessary to get the 
agreement of all countries in the CIS. Ivan Korotchenya, before 
his arrival in Tbilisi, had already visited the central Asian 
states, and intends in the next few days to visit Baku and 
Yerevan, and then go to Moldova and Ukraine. 
  Concerning the question of a possible date for the 
introduction of peacekeeping forces into the conflict zone, Ivan 
Korotchenya said: 
  [Begin Korotchenya recording] By 10 June. Well, 10 to 15 
June. On this there is probably a need for a final decision 
which will be taken by the Russian president. [end recording] 
  [Keliselidze] Eduard Shevardnadze in his turn thanked the 
CIS 
leaders who responded positively to Yeltsin's appeal for the 
introduction of peacekeeping forces into the Georgian-Abkhazian 
conflict zone. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

