<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Georgia Importing Weapons From Russia, East Europe </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Georgia Importing Weapons From Russia, East Europe </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3105164594 Tbilisi IBERIA in Georgian 1400 GMT 31 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3105164594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tbilisi IBERIA </F>
<F P=105>  Georgian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tbilisi, 31 May -- Apart from the weapons they have 
been receiving from the Transcaucasus Military District (since 
1992), the authorities in the Republic of Georgia have also been 
buying weapons (mostly, firearms) on the territory of the 
Russian Federation and from eastern European countries, namely, 
Poland, Czechoslovakia, and Romania. 
  A small consignment (not more than several hundred weapons) 
of Polish-made 7.62mm-calibre collapsible Kalashnikov automatic 
guns has been imported from Poland, while 7.62mm-calibre 
submachine guns have been imported from Czeckoslovakia and 
distributed among security officers guarding government 
buildings. 
  The largest number of Kalashnikov automatic guns arrived in 
Georgia from Romania. (It must be noted that Romanian-made 
Kalashnikovs are of rather poor quality.) The first consignment 
of (7.62-calibre) automatic guns came in two marine cargo 
containers aboard a Romanian ship and was unloaded near Batumi 
in 1992. Since no one appeared to have ordered the weapons, it 
was assumed that they had been ordered by the government of 
ex-Georgian president Gamsakhurdia. 
  In 1993, Shevardnadze's government imported up to 8,000 
5.45mm-calibre Romanian-made Kalashnikov automatic guns (for the 
price of about $120 each). 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

