<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Crimean Leaders Believe Government Crisis Looming </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Crimean Leaders Believe Government Crisis Looming </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3105131794 Moscow Radio Rossii Network in Russian 1000 GMT 
31 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD3105131794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radio Rossii Network </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Deputies of the Crimean parliament were faced today 
by the same question as at previous sittings -- the question of 
the republican Cabinet of Ministers. Roman Babayan reports from 
Simferopol: 
  [Babayan] The fact is that almost all of last week the 
deputies, together with Crimean President Yuriy Meshkov and 
Deputy Prime Minister Yevgeniy Saburov, discussed the 
nominations for future republican ministers. But they failed to 
reach any decisions. Each side gives their own explanation of 
this. 
  Deputy Prime Minister Yevgeniy Saburov believes that the 
deputies are being obstinate over the issue of approving the 
Cabinet of Ministers because the parliamentarians do not want to 
have a pro-presidential government in the Crimea. Yevgeniy 
Saburov noted that in the very near future deputies of the 
Crimean parliament will try to kick out Yuriy Meshkov. 
According to Saburov, there is a situation developing today in 
the Crimea which is like the September-October 1993 Moscow 
situation. 
  President Yuriy Meshkov is not as categorical as the Crimean 
deputy prime minister. However, after the parliament again 
refused to approve the composition of the Cabinet of Ministers, 
he also stated that the Crimea is on the verge of a third 
government crisis. 
  As for the parliamentarians themselves, they explain that 
they are taking these actions because the people put forward for 
nomination are incompetent. 
  Whatever the reasons, as a result the Crimea still does not 
have a government, and in consequence starting the process of 
bringing the Crimean economy out of the bad situation in which 
it is at present is being postponed indefinitely. 

</TEXT>

