<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Crimean Official Mocks `Opposition Supreme Soviet' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Crimean Official Mocks `Opposition Supreme Soviet' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0106120694 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0939 
GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0106120694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By UKRINFORM correspondent Lev Ryabchikov] </F>
  [Text] Simferopol, 1 Jun (ITAR-TASS) -- "I have no idea who 
belongs to this opposition Supreme Soviet." This is how Viktor 
Mezhak, deputy chairman of the Crimean Supreme Soviet, commented 
on the statement by supporters of the deautonomization of the 
Crimea, who call themselves the "Crimean Opposition Supreme 
Soviet", which was broadcast Tuesday. He said there is nothing 
new in such statements. "Some Ukrainian public organizations 
have previously made demands for the dissolution of the Crimean 
parliament and for the introduction of presidential rule." 
  "It is incomprehensible," Viktor Mezhak said, "why, 
broadcasting this information, journalists were not interested 
in who created this `opposition Supreme Soviet', who gave it the 
power to come out with a statement in the name of the Crimeans? 
I think this was done in order to whip up passions around the 
Crimea just a bit more." 
  Stressing the desire of the Crimean people's elected 
representatives to tackle all the problems around the 
negotiating table with their counterparts from Kiev, Viktor 
Mezhak said: "We expect the Ukrainian parliamentarians to 
continue the dialogue on settling our relations. We are 
counting that they will come to the Crimea this Friday." 

</TEXT>

