<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Black Sea Fleet Makes Ukraine Close Naval Radar in Odessa </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Black Sea Fleet Makes Ukraine Close Naval Radar in Odessa </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3105145894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1436 GMT 31 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3105145894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Anatoly Kholodyuk] </F>
  [Text] Sevastopol May 31 TASS -- The naval radar system 
near the Ukrainian Black Sea Port of Odessa will cease to 
operate Wednesday as the Black Sea Fleet command refused to 
share it with Ukrainian Navy authorities. 
  Spokesman for the Ukrainian Navy Oleg Chubuk told TASS on 
Tuesday that the radar stops functioning because "the Black Sea 
Fleet has not expressed readiness to cooperate with the 
Ukrainian Navy in running the facility and exchanging data 
monitored in the north-western part of the Black Sea". 
  According to the source, the fleet command has twice ignored 
Ukrainian messages requesting such cooperation. 
  The Black Sea Fleet operates a network of radars called 
"Mars", one of which is located near Odessa. 
  Tensions between the Ukrainian and Black Sea Navies flared 
up 
last month when radar equipment was transferred from Odessa to 
the fleet's main base in Sevastopol without Ukrainian consent. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

