<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nunn on Cooperation in Nuclear Nonproliferation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Nunn on Cooperation in Nuclear Nonproliferation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3105134994 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1015 
GMT 31 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD3105134994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Arseniy Mironov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 31 May -- "Russia, the United States, and 
the other nuclear powers must recognize that it is in their 
common interests to fight the proliferation of nuclear weapons," 
Sam Nunn, chairman of the U.S. Senate Armed Services Committee, 
said at a news conference here today. At the request of 
ITAR-TASS, he commented upon reports in the British media that 
the possibility of the special services of the Russian 
Federation, the United States, and Great Britain cooperating on 
collecting information on attempts by certain countries to 
create their own nuclear weapons is being discussed at the 
diplomatic level. 
  S. Nunn stressed that ideas on this kind of cooperation had 
been put forward by Senator Warren, by experts of the U.S. 
Senate Armed Services Committee, and by himself a few years ago. 
The senator said: "It is a tragic paradox that now that 
confrontation between the nuclear powers is a thing of the past, 
our countries are defenseless in the face of a nuclear threat 
from terrorist groups." The report that the special services 
have begun to hold talks on cooperating in this sphere is "good 
news," Senator Nunn noted. 

</TEXT>

