<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Working Meeting Discusses Russian-U.S. Maneuvers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Working Meeting Discusses Russian-U.S. Maneuvers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3105202294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1845 GMT 31 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3105202294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] It is expedient to hold the first joint exercises of 
the Russian and American peacekeeping forces scheduled for this 
summer in the Orenburg region on the territory of the United 
States. This conclusion was reached in the course of a working 
meeting between the Russian parliamentarians and members of the 
American Senate held on Tuesday in Moscow. This information was 
made public at a press conference attended by the Chairman of 
the State Duma Committee on Defense Sergey Yushenkov, head of 
the analogous committee of the US Senate Sam Nunn, leader of the 
State Duma committee on international affairs Vladimir Lukin, 
and Senator Robert Couts. 
  Responding to INTERFAX, Yushenkov indicated that "a campaign 
of protest against the presence of the American forces in the 
center of Russia is being waged in Orenburg and around it, it is 
difficult to conduct exercises in such a situation." However, 
the new variant providing for the exercises in the U.S. "will be 
subject to obstruction -- now due to the spending of state funds 
for the transfer of our forces across the ocean," Yushenkov 
believes. 
  At the same time Yushenkov and Nunn believe that it is 
necessary to conduct such joint maneuvers "as a symbol of 
confidence and partnership between our countries." In 
particular, Nunn declared that "the American people will welcome 
Russian servicemen on their soil." 

</TEXT>

