<H3> <TI>   Congress Cuts U.S. Aid to CIS; Russia's Share Reduced </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Congress Cuts U.S. Aid to CIS; Russia's Share Reduced </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM3105152694 Moscow IZVESTIYA in Russian 31 May 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> PM3105152694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow IZVESTIYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Aleksandr Shalnev report: "U.S. Aid to the CIS To Be </F>
Reduced"] 
  [Text] The U.S. Congress House of Representatives has 
appropriated $875 million for programs to assist reforms in 
Russia and other countries of the former Union in the 1995 
fiscal year, which begins 1 October of this year. 
  This is $25 million less than planned by President Clinton's 
administration. According to the administration's proposals, 
Russia will receive a little less than one-half of the allocated 
sum. This is Washington's new policy; in previous years it has, 
on the contrary, alloted Russia first place in determining the 
proportion of aid to be assigned. 

</TEXT>

