<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   ROK Interested in Boosting Cooperation With Russia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    ROK Interested in Boosting Cooperation With Russia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3105135994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1242 GMT 31 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3105135994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By BUSINESS-TASS correspondent Irina Bolshova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 31 TASS -- Despite some unsettled 
problems in Russian-South Korean economic relations, South 
Korean Government and business quarters display interest in 
developing trade, economic, scientific and technical cooperation 
with greater number of Russian enterprises and firms and in 
establishing contacts with the administrations of Russian 
regions, Russian Foreign Economic Relations Minister Oleg 
Davydov told BUSINESS-TASS here on Tuesday. 
  The unsettled nature of credit relations is the main problem 
in bilateral contacts. This greatly limits the sphere of 
cooperation at the interstate level, the minister noted. 
  Under the pretext of unsettled Russian debts, South Korea 
continues to enforce several secret limitations on trade and 
economic relations with Russia, including abstention from state 
crediting and insurance of foreign trade deals and investment 
projects. 
  This creates some difficulties, especially for small and 
medium South Korean firms, Davydov stressed. 
  Nevertheless, the year 1993 registered growth in 
Russian-South Korean trade turnover which was worth 1.5 billion 
U.S. dollars, the minister said. Russian export nearly doubled 
as compared with 1992, totalling 960 million dollars. 
  Import from South Korea rose by 45 per cent, amounting to 
530 
million dollars. "I state with regret," Davydov noted, "that 
Russian export to South Korea consisted mostly of raw materials 
(98.4 per cent)." 
  On the other hand, a trend for purchasing ready-made 
consumer 
goods rather than industrial equipment became more prominent in 
imports. 
  It is expected that Davydov will hold talks on current 
issues 
of Russian-South Korean trade and economic cooperation with 
South Korean President Kim Yong-sam who will arrive in Moscow on 
an official visit on Wednesday. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

