<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rybkin Meets Kuwaitis, Comments on Yeltsin Decrees </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rybkin Meets Kuwaitis, Comments on Yeltsin Decrees </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3005112694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1027 GMT 30 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3005112694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS parliamentary correspondent Ivan Novikov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 30 TASS -- "President Boris Yeltsin's 
latest six decrees on economic policy create conditions for the 
promotion of Russian entrepreneurship and for raising the 
activity of foreign investors," Duma Speaker Ivan Rybkin said 
here today during his meeting with the parliamentary delegation 
of Kuwait. "It goes without saying that these documents will 
help promote business activity in the country," he noted. 
  Touching on relationships between the Russian Federation and 
Kuwait, the speaker said that their cooperation "could be more 
resultative and effective", including in the sphere of 
parliamentary contacts. "Frankly speaking, both sides have 
still not used all the available opportunities," he added. 
  Head of the Kuwait delegation Ahmad 'Abd-al-'Aziz al-Sa'dun, 
chairman of the Kuwait National Assembly, thanked Russia for its 
stand of principle vis-a-vis Iraq, which had unleashed an 
aggression against his country. "We want this stand to remain 
immutable," the guest noted. 
  Rybkin assured the Kuwait MPs [members of parliament] that 
the Russian attitude to the friendly Kuwaiti state was 
irreversible. "We want all the resolutions of the [UN] Security 
Council, linked with the Gulf war, to be fully implemented," he 
stressed. "At the same time," Rybkin stated, "we are perfectly 
aware that it is impossible to live in conditions when there is 
no peace and no war. It is necessary to achieve a situation when 
the two peoples would live in conditions of good-neighbourship 
and peace. The Russian MPs, together with their Kuwait 
colleagues, must do their best in this noble effort." 

</TEXT>

