<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Denies Arms Sales to Yemen </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Ministry Denies Arms Sales to Yemen </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3105135594 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1135 
GMT 31 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD3105135594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondents Boris Krivoshey and </F>
Aleksandr Krylovich] 
  [Text] Moscow, 31 May -- The allegations being circulated 
by some parties that Russia is supplying arms and military 
equipment to Yemen are wholly unsubstantiated, Grigoriy Karasin, 
director of the Press and Information Department of the Russian 
Federation Foreign Ministry, told a news conference today. "The 
Russian Federation is not supplying the Yemenis with 
special-purpose equipment, either directly or through a third 
country", he stressed. 
  The Russian Foreign Ministry spokesman said that even last 
year, long before the armed conflict began, Russia decided to 
halt supplies of arms and military equipment to Yemen following 
the exacerbation of intra-Yemeni discord. Russia did this on 
the grounds that supplying weapons to warring parties 
contradicts its principled approach, which aims to achieve the 
earliest possible settlement of the conflict by political 
methods. Grigoriy Karasin pointed out that the Russian Foreign 
Ministry is taking this line in contacts with both states and is 
encouraging them to act in the same way. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

