<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chechen State of Emergency Not Seen as Security Threat </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chechen State of Emergency Not Seen as Security Threat </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3105144694 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1310 
GMT 31 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD3105144694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Mikhail Shevtsov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 31 May -- The fact that, in accordance with 
a decree issued on Monday [30 May] by the Russian president, a 
number of populated areas in Malgobekskiy and Sunzhenskiy Rayons 
of Ingushetia have been included in the state of emergency is 
not regarded by official Groznyy as a direct threat to the 
national security of Chechnya. Movladi Udugov, head of the 
Chechen Department of Information and Press, told this to an 
ITAR-TASS correspondent today in a telephone interview. 
  He noted that the preliminary analysis of the new decree "on 
the introduction of a state of emergency in parts of the 
territory of the Republic of North Ossetia and the Republic of 
Ingushetia" has not led to any undue concern on the part of the 
Chechen leadership. Movladi Udugov said that the villages in 
Sunzhenskiy and Malgobekskiy Rayons, which have been included in 
the state of emergency zone, are not under dispute. They were 
Ingush before the administrative and territorial division of 
1934, when the Chechen-Ingush ASSR was set up. 
  At the same time, Movladi Udugov said, official Groznyy 
considers it unjustified to extend the state of emergency zone 
on the territory of Ingushetia. In his view, "Boris Yeltsin is 
artificially pushing the expansion of the emergency zone in 
order to create tension with Chechnya." 
  Movladi Udugov believes that because Ingushetia is a part of 
Russia, whereas Chechnya regards itself to be outside Russia, in 
principle the Chechen-Ingush border should be defined. Ruslan 
Aushev and Dzhokhar Dudayev have therefore signed an appropriate 
treaty on the principles of defining borders. The borders 
established before 1934 were taken as the basis for this. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

