<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-105 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  31 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Kozyrev Remarks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on Kozyrev Remarks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3105184894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1335 GMT 31 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3105184894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow has no intention of giving up weapons exports 
to third world countries unilaterally without prior talks with 
the West, Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev said in Moscow 
on Tuesday. At a meeting with U.S. congressmen led by Senator 
Sam Nunn, he dwelt upon Russian arms exports to Iran which are 
causing western concern. 
  "Let us work together over the rules of weapons exports (to 
third countries)", Kozyrev said. "Asking Russia to undertake 
commitment not to export weapons(to Iran) unilaterally as a 
condition for talks on the issue is not only out of line with 
the spirit of partnership with our western allies, but it also 
brings to mind the worst in our common history", he said. 
  About Nagorno-Karabakh, the minister said that Russia was 
alone prepared to send peacekeepers to that area of conflict 
poisoning the situation on both sides of the Caucasus and posing 
threat to its southern fringes. 
  "Meanwhile, we are being accused of neo-imperialism on the 
grounds that a political solution must be found to the conflict 
before sending peacekeepers to the region", he said. 
  Kozyrev said that instead of the assistance Moscow would 
welcome, the West preferred to act as inspector driving in a 
wedge in efforts by Russia and the CSCE to try to settle the 
conflict. "This is not a partnership approach", he said. 
  For details, refer to Diplomatic Panorama of May 31. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-38663 </DOCNO>
