<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia, CIA Help To Arm, Train New Military Unit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russia, CIA Help To Arm, Train New Military Unit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM0106135594 Moscow KOMSOMOLSKAYA PRAVDA in Russian 1 Jun 94 
p 1 </F>

<F P=103> PM0106135594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KOMSOMOLSKAYA PRAVDA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report from "Inform" column: "Georgia Has Its </F>
Own Special Forces"] 
  [Text] A Georgian State Security Service special-purpose, 
assault-landing brigade has been reviewed in the village of 
Mukhrovani in East Georgia. Talking to journalists, Igor 
Giorgadze, chairman of Georgia's State Security Service, said 
that this subunit has been trained at the Russian special 
services' training centers. The Russian Armed Forces have 
provided the new Georgian special-purpose forces with new modern 
arms and equipment free of charge. The assault-landing brigade 
comprises tanks, armored hardware, artillery, a crack "Alfa" 
subunit, and an antiterrorist squad. The latter has been 
trained, armed, and equipped by the U.S. CIA. 
  Newspapers in Tbilisi reported that the upkeep of the 
Georgian special forces will cost the Republic 5 billion Russian 
rubles a year. 

</TEXT>

