<DATE1>  2 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin, Kim Yong-Sam Sign Partnership Declaration </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin, Kim Yong-Sam Sign Partnership Declaration </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0206091294 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0823 
GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0206091294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Vladimir Solntsev] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 2 Jun -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin and 
ROK President Kim Yong-sam, who is in Moscow on an official 
visit, today signed a joint Russian-Korean declaration in the 
Kremlin on completion of their bilateral summit. The document 
proclaims the raising of bilateral relations to a level of 
mutually complementary constructive partnership, and reflects 
the two sides' approaches to the main problems of both world 
politics, including the nuclear problem on the Korean Peninsula, 
and to questions of cooperation between Moscow and Seoul in the 
economic, political, and other spheres. 
  A number of other bilateral documents were also signed, 
including intergovernmental agreements on cooperation in 
protection of the environment, on preventing incidents at sea 
outside territorial waters, and on the protection of migratory 
birds, and also a protocol on consultations between the 
Ministries of Foreign Affairs of the Russian Federation and the 
ROK. 
  The South Korean side was handed more than 200 archive 
documents relating to the Korean War during 1950-53. They 
include correspondence conducted by the then leaders of the 
USSR, the DPRK, and the PRC, with telegrams from Josip Stalin 
and Mao Tse-tung, and they reveal the degree of the former 
Soviet Union's involvement in the Korean War. "History should 
stand revealed in its true form," a high-ranking official of the 
Russian Federation's Foreign Ministry said in a conversation 
with the ITAR-TASS correspondent. He said the handing over of 
archive documents would make it possible to "close one of the 
pages of the past." At the same time, the sides are united in 
the opinion that the sad past in relations between Moscow and 
Seoul should remain in the past and should not affect the 
present and future. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-38684 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov106_a_94006" </HT>


