<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Warns DPRK of Sanctions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin Warns DPRK of Sanctions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0206103994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1020 GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0206103994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow June 2 TASS -- Russia believes it is yet 
premature to speak about sanctions against North Korea, but if 
the latter decides to secede from the nuclear non-proliferation 
regime Moscow will insist on a gradual approach to sanctions. 
  "If North Korea strives to secede from the Nuclear 
Non-Proliferation Treaty, Russia will be forced to gradually 
begin solving the problem: make a warning and then the world 
community should adopt a decision on imposing sanctions on North 
Korea", Russian President Boris Yeltsin told a press conference 
on Thursday. He added, however, that it is premature to speak 
about sanctions as no decision has been yet adopted on convening 
an international conference on the nuclear problem of North 
Korea. 
  Yeltsin also said that both the Russian and South Korean 
leaderships are "greatly concerned about what is happenong in 
the People's Democratic Republic of Korea (PDRK) taken into 
consideration its direct closeness to the Russian eastern 
borders". 
  "We cannot be indifferent to how the PDRK treats the earlier 
signed Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty and are ready to act", 
Yeltsin said and admitted that the problem has been delayed for 
too long and "has no positive solution so far". 
  The Russian president said that he may discuss the problem 
with his US counterpart. 
  Speaking on the Soviet-North Korean friendship and 
cooperation treaty of 1961, Yeltsin recalled that an amendment 
had been introduced to its first article which envisaged an 
immediate military help to Pyongyang if the latter was attacked. 
Now "there is no strict provision envisaging that we help and 
side with the PDRK", Yeltsin said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

