<H3> <TI>   Russian, Greek Foreign Ministers Meet in Moscow </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russian, Greek Foreign Ministers Meet in Moscow </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Kozyrev, Papoulias Begin Talks </H4>

<F P=102> LD0106110394 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0940 
GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0106110394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Yuriy Kozlov and </F>
Valeriy Sevryukov] 
  [Text] Moscow, 1 June -- "The visit by the President of the 
Russian Federation, Boris Yeltsin, to Athens last year has set 
Russian-Greek relations into full swing. After many centuries 
of spiritual political and historical proximity, these relations 
have revived with the breath of fresh air." This had been stated 
by RF Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev before he started talks 
with Greek Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulias here today. 
  The head of the Russian foreign policy department said that 
he attached great importance to the current meeting, considering 
the big role Greece is playing in the Balkans and nowadays in 
Europe as head of the European Union. 
  The talks are centred on the issues concerning bilateral 
relations and preparations for the visit to Russia of the Greek 
prime-minister Andreas Papandreou at the end of the year. 
Regarding foreign policy, the sides intend to discuss the 
situation in the former Yugoslavia and the Balkans as a whole, 
as well as the Cypriot and the Near East problems. 

</TEXT>

