<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian, Greek Foreign Ministers Meet in Moscow </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russian, Greek Foreign Ministers Meet in Moscow </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Shokhin Seeks Tighter Economic Links </H4>

<F P=102> LD0106191094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1620 GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0106191094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russia wants to upgrade Russian-Greek economic 
relations by launching new large scale projects, Deputy Prime 
Minister Aleksandr Shokhin told Interfax following his meeting 
with Greek Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulias. 
  These projects include the construction of an oil pipeline 
from Burgas, Bulgaria, into Greece. Shokhin said that this 
would be a new export route by-passing the Bosphorus and 
Dardanelles which might be closed for environmental reasons. 
  Under another project, Greek ship-owners would contribute to 
the revival of the Russian merchant fleet. 
  To the best of Interfax's knowledge, during the Papoulias 
visit to Moscow the two sides held intensive talks on the 
continuation of the construction of an alumina works and gas 
pipeline in Greece with Russian participation. 

</TEXT>

