<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Churkin Continues Consultations on Bosnia Settlement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Churkin Continues Consultations on Bosnia Settlement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM0106161594 Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA in Russian 2 Jun 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> PM0106161594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [ITAR-TASS correspondent Andrey Naryshkin report: "Is June </F>
the `Key' Month?"] 
  [Text] Zagreb, 1 Jun -- Moscow believes that June should 
be a "key" month in the attainment of a Bosnian peace settlement 
and possibly in resolving the whole set of problems in the 
Yugoslav crisis, Vitaliy Churkin, the Russian president's 
special representative, said Tuesday [31 May] in Zagreb during 
an exclusive interview with your ITAR-TASS correspondent. 
  Speaking about holding a special summit meeting on the 
Bosnian settlement, V. Churkin noted that "if this summit has 
not been held by mid-June, say, more attention will probably be 
paid to Yugoslav affairs during the G-7 meeting in Naples, which 
will a G-8 meeting for the first time, with Russia's full 
participation in the discussion of political problems." 
  Commenting on the content of today's talks in Belgrade with 
Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic and also with Serbian 
leaders from Bosnia and Krajina, the Russian deputy foreign 
minister noted that priority during these talks was given to two 
issues -- the situation in Bosnia, with the emphasis on 
attaining an agreement on the cessation of hostilities; and the 
preparations for the next Geneva meeting, as well as for the 
resumption of talks between Zagreb and Knin. 
  The Russian president's special representative plans to meet 
with Alija Izetbegovic, chairman of the Bosnia-Herzegovina 
Presidium, and Bosnian Premier Haris Silajdzic in Sarajevo. 
  Tuesday evening V. Churkin was received in Zagreb by 
Croatian 
President Franjo Tudjman. "We had a very good discussion during 
which Franjo Tudjman once again reaffirmed his high opinion of 
Russia's role in the Yugoslav settlement and Croatia's interest 
in continuing dialogue not only with Knin but also with Belgrade 
and in the overall normalization of bilateral relations, which 
play a key role in the complex of problems involved in the 
Yugoslav crisis," the Russian diplomat said. 

</TEXT>

