<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Departs for Geneva Talks on Bosnia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Departs for Geneva Talks on Bosnia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0206085994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0846 GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0206085994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Andrey Naryshkin] </F>
  [Text] Zagreb June 2 TASS -- The UN and Russian envoys to 
former Yugoslavia, Yasushi Akashi and Vitaliy Churkin left 
Zagreb for Geneva early on Thursday for a meeting on Bosnia, 
TASS was told at the Zagreb headquarters of the UN peace-keepers. 
  The Geneva talks were in question until the last moment 
because Akashi had no guarantees that Bosnian Serbs would stand 
up to their promise and withdraw their remaining units from the 
3-kilometre zone around Gorazde. The Muslim leadership refused 
to participate in the talks if the Serbs do not withdraw. 
  On Thursday Akashi received a message from Bosnian Serb 
leader Radovan Karadzic confirming that the troops would be 
withdrawn. 
  Churkin told TASS that the degree of readiness for the talks 
at which a complete end to hostilities in Bosnia is to be 
discussed, is "very high". He added that "serious discussions" 
would go [as received] about a number of details, but "chances 
for success are very high". 

</TEXT>

