<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Anatoliy Yurkin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 1 TASS -- Russian land troops stationed 
in the Kaliningrad region pose no threat to the neighbouring 
countries, including Poland, Commander of the Russian Land 
Troops Colonel-General Vladimir Semenov said. 
  In an exclusive interview with ITAR-TASS on Wednesday, 
Semenov said that the troops in the Kaliningrad region, Russia's 
westernmost enclave, are not an "armoured fist threatening the 
Baltic Sea countries", and fulfill the tasks aimed at ensuring 
the national security of Russia. 
  He also stressed that Russia strictly observes its 
international commitments. Semenov said there are as many tanks 
and troops in the Kaliningrad regions as is necessary to ensure 
Russia's security. 

