<H3> <TI>   Grachev Meets With German Official </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Grachev Meets With German Official </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM0106114394 Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA in Russian 1 Jun 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> PM0106114394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Ravil Mustafin report: "Meeting in the Ministry of </F>
Defense"] 
  [Text] On 30 May Army General Pavel Grachev, Russian 
Federation minister of defense, held a meeting with Michaela 
Geiger, parliamentary state secretary of the FRG Ministry of 
Defense in the Bundestag. Pavel Grachev noted that Russia's 
proposals on the NATO "Partnership for Peace" program were 
greeted with understanding among practically all the 
participants in the talks during the recent visit by the head of 
the Russian military department to the NATO headquarters in 
Brussels. Only certain details remain to be elaborated. Russia 
will be able to join the "Partnership for Peace" program within 
two or three weeks, P. Grachev noted. But for this to happen, 
Western countries should study these proposals and draw up a 
document through diplomatic channels which would express 
agreement with Russia's proposals. 
  The Russian defense minister's optimism is also connected 
with the fact that when he was in Brussels, Pavel Grachev "saw 
support for the Russian proposals on the part of FRG Defense 
Minister Volker Ruehe." "The greater the country the more they 
understand us," the head of the Russian military department 
noted. Unfortunately, unlike the ministers of defense of NATO 
countries, from whom Pavel Grachev perceived support and "a good 
attitude toward me and toward Russia," to use his own words, the 
CIS countries do not always display understanding toward the 
problems facing Moscow. 

</TEXT>

