<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Denies Experts Making Weapons in PRC </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official Denies Experts Making Weapons in PRC </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0106184594 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1812 GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0106184594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Vladimir Solntsev] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 1 TASS -- About 1,000 Russian 
specialists work in China, well-informed sources told ITAR-TASS 
on Wednesday. 
  However, the sources denied reports published by the U.S. 
NEWS AND WORLD REPORT magazine that "thousands" of scientists 
and technicians from the former Soviet Union work under 
contracts in China and help design and produce modern weapons. 
  "I do not rule out that there may be contracts under which 
our technical specialists go to China. But I doubt it very much 
that there are so many of them. All the more so because so 
sensitive spheres of cooperation are involved. I think that if 
such cases exist, there are only a few of them," a Russian 
Foreign Ministry top official said. 
  "`Thousands' is an absurd figure. Until lately we did not 
have facts that someone worked in the sphere of arms 
production," an official with the Russian foreign intelligence 
service said. 
  However, other sources said that China has certain interest 
in Russian specialists, particularly in the sphere of aircraft 
building. Those who go to China are either of no interest for 
western countries, or know too much to be allowed to go to the 
west. In China they earn about 1,000 U.S. dollars a month on the 
average. This is much less than they could make in the west, but 
much more than they earned in Russia, the sources said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

