<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bank Chief Seeks Break in Access by Foreign Banks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bank Chief Seeks Break in Access by Foreign Banks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0106151394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1321 GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0106151394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By BUSINESS-TASS correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 1 TASS -- President of the Association 
of Russian Banks Sergey Yegorov went on record today for a "time 
out" in the admission of foreign banks to the Russian market. 
  "In principle," he told a press conference here, "we favour 
foreign investments in the Russian economy, including the 
banking sphere. However, the national banking system is yet in 
the making. It is not strong enough to face tough competition 
from major foreign banks on the domestic market. Hence, there 
is no point in trying to `butt the oak'. We need time to gather 
strength." 
  Yegorov noted that Russian banks ran up against great 
difficulties whenever they tried to open their offices, let 
alone subsidiaries, in Western countries. 
  "Restrictions on the admission of foreign banks to the 
Russian market," he said, "will not last for centuries, but only 
for concrete time periods, necessary to give the Russian 
commercial banks a breather so that they could gather strength 
and build up a Russian national banking system." 
  Addressing a press conference here on Tuesday, Chairman of 
the Russian Central Bank Viktor Gerashchenko said that some 
restrictions on the work of foreign banks in Russia might be 
lifted in the foreseeable future. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

