<F P=100> WESTERN REGION </F>
<F P=101> Belarus </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kebich Outlines Presidential Election Campaign Policy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kebich Outlines Presidential Election Campaign Policy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0106122594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1012 GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0106122594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] If elected as the first Belarusian president, 
present Belarusian Premier Vyacheslav Kebich will undertake 
urgent measures in order to stop the run-away growth in prices 
and carry out wide-scale actions to fight crime. 
  The presidential elections in Belarus will take place on 23 
June. A total of six candidates for presidency have been 
officially registered, including Kebich, Belarusian parliament's 
ex-speaker Stanislav Shushkevich, the Belarusian opposition 
People's Front leader Zenon Poznyak and Communist leader Vasili 
Novikov. 
  Kebich said in an exclusive interview with INTERFAX that, if 
elected the president, he would carry out the agreement on the 
merging of the Russian and Belarusian monetary systems. Kebich 
is considered one of the most likely winners of the presidential 
race. 
  However, he emphasized that the budgets of the two countries 
would not be merged. Kebich said that only two budget items 
would be coordinated -- the deficit and the amount of money 
issued. 
  Speaking about his contenders, Kebich feared that Zenon 
Poznyak might win the presidential elections. Kebich suggested 
that if Poznyak be elected, Belarus would face war, bloodshed 
and elimination of human rights and liberties. 
  He added that if the People's Front won the elections, this 
would mean a catastrophe for the whole Belarusian people. 
Kebich confirmed his suggestion by referring to the recent 
statement by Poznyak in the media. Poznyak had put forward 
territorial claims to Russia, Lithuania and Poland. Kebich said 
this was a dangerous policy which would lead to bloodshed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

