<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Public Accord Treaty Legitimizes Tuva's Role in Federation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Public Accord Treaty Legitimizes Tuva's Role in Federation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0106191194 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0803 
GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0106191194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Yevgeniy Sobetskiy] </F>
  [Text] Kyzyl, 1 Jun--The question of the legality of Tuva's 
joining Russia in 1944 is now completely meaningless. Republic 
President Sherig-ool Oorzhak said this on Tuesday during the 
festive ceremony of the signing of the Public Accord Treaty. 
This document was signed by representatives of all authorities, 
political parties--including the Communist Party--all public 
associations, and all religious persuasions. 
  The president addressed the fact that certain forces in the 
republic--first of all the nationalists--are still disputing the 
lawfulness of this decision made 50 years ago on the pretext 
that it was made by a narrow circle of leaders. Having voted at 
the December 1993 referendum in favor of the republic's 
Constitution-- which regards the republic as an integral part of 
Russia--Tuva's multiethnic people thus legitimized the 1944 
decision. In the president's view, the Public Accord Treaty 
plays a similar role today. 

</TEXT>

