<H3> <TI>   Novgorod Farms Stop Sowing; Administration `Deaf' to Pleas </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Novgorod Farms Stop Sowing; Administration `Deaf' to Pleas </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM0206075194 Moscow SOVETSKAYA ROSSIYA in Russian 2 Jun 94 p 
1 </F>

<F P=103> PM0206075194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow SOVETSKAYA ROSSIYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Pavel Orlov report: "Pasture Abandoned"] </F>
  [Text] Nizhniy Novgorod -- More than 20 agricultural 
enterprises in the Nizhniy Novgorod area have not carried out 
sowing work this spring. Sowing is unprofitable this year, 
their leaders say. Bank loans are extortionate and the state 
does not buy your output. 
  The renaming and reorganization of kolkhozes is not saving 
them from collapse. Meat and milk production is a loss-maker 
under current economic conditions. For instance, the 
"Ptitseprom" owes more than 10 billion rubles for mixed feed, 
and poultry factories are on the point of collapse. 
  Requests from farmers for partial compensation for their 
expenditure and for concessionary rates for energy fall on deaf 
ears. The oblast administration considers its most important 
task to be not to ensure stable provision of home-produced food 
to the population, but to divide up the land, creating a huge 
number of landowners...with spades. 

</TEXT>

