<F P=100> Tajikistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Opposition To Discuss Refugees, Border </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Opposition To Discuss Refugees, Border </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0106182994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1427 GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0106182994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Presidential Bulletin" feature: Correspondents </F>
Igor Porshnev, Vitaliy Trubetskoy and others] 
  [Text] Dushanbe officials want to discuss the return of all 
Tajik refugees from Afghanistan and elsewhere and security of 
the Tajik-Afghan border during the talks with the opposition 
that are scheduled to be held in Tehran in mid-June. First 
Deputy Chairman Abdujalil Dostiyev of the country's Supreme 
Soviet told INTERFAX that the refugees who had fought for the 
opposition in the civil war would not be prosecuted because they 
were covered by the amnesty. 
  Tajik Foreign Minister Rashid Alimov said that no final date 
had been set for the Tehran talks. He would not mention any 
date so as not to harm the negotiating process. 
  Alimov said that there would be no changes in the Tajik 
Government delegation. 
  INTERFAX Note: In the Moscow round of talks on 5-19 April 
the two sides agreed on the agenda which includes now a 
ceasefire, return of the refugees and subsequent consultations. 
The opposition, notably Akbar Turajonzoda, one of its leaders, 
wants the government delegation, now headed by Labor and 
Employment Minister Shukurjon Zukhurov, to be upgraded. 
  Observers in Dushanbe are concerned that the recent killings 
of Russian border guards in Tajikistan may have a negative 
impact on the talks. Meanwhile, General Anatoliy Kuptsov, 
deputy security minister, dismissed the speculation that these 
killings were politically motivated. He said that these were 
common crimes. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

