<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kravchuk Urges Gradual Solution of Black Sea Fleet Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kravchuk Urges Gradual Solution of Black Sea Fleet Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0106143694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1315 GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0106143694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Viktor Demidenko and Mikhail </F>
Melnik] 
  [Text] Kiev June 1 TASS -- "The completion of the 
negotiation process between Ukraine and Russia over the division 
of the Black Sea Fleet is vital for settling the Crimean 
problem," Ukrainian President Leonid Kravchuk said. 
  In his address to the Ukrainian parliament on the situation 
in the Crimea on Wednesday, Kravchuk said that "we must not 
demand that Russia immediately withdraw its ships from 
Sevastopol. This would be wrong from the strategic point of 
view in the first place." 
  Ukraine cannot ban Russia from keeping a navy force in the 
Black Sea. History has bound Russia and Ukraine to live in 
peace and friendship and be equal partners, Kravchuk said. He 
added that the question of the fleet is the "question of Ukraine 
and Russia." 
  He stressed that it must be solved gradually, without 
causing 
the situation to worsen. He agreed that the fleet should be 
divided and based in different places, but stressed the need to 
determine the status of the Russian part of the fleet which will 
be located in Ukraine. 
  Ukraine is seeking to find such a solution which would "meet 
the national interests and take into account Russia's security 
needs in the south," Kravchuk said. He noted that in the future 
Russia will have to set up a navy base on its own territory. 
  The Ukrainian leader emphasised that after the recent talks 
in Moscow between the Russian and Ukrainian official delegations 
"some details of the agreements on the fleet are beginning to 
take shape." He said that the talks will resume in the near 
future. 
  Kravchuk stressed that the Crimean issue is vital not only 
for Ukraine and the Crimea, but also "all European states and 
the world community." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

