<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deputies Offer Solutions to Crimean Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Deputies Offer Solutions to Crimean Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0106160294 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1500 
GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0106160294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Viktor Demidenko and Mikhail </F>
Melnik] 
  [Text] Kiev, 1 Jun -- "Official Simferopol must remember 
that Crimea is a constituent part of Ukraine, and therefore it 
ought to bring the Constitution of the autonomous republic in 
line with Ukrainian legislation." That was the main idea of 
today's speeches by Ukrainian parliamentarians during the debate 
on the "Crimean question." 
  Some deputies demanded that the Constitution of the Crimean 
republic be suspended until it is brought in line with the 
Constitution of Ukraine, and that the population of the 
peninsula should abide by the laws of the Ukrainian state. Some 
said that the powers of the Crimean Supreme Council must be 
suspended early. In this connection, the Ukrainian president 
was asked to set up executive bodies of state power on the 
territory of Crimea and to ensure that Ukraine's constitutional 
norms are observed. 
  Many speakers believe that the situation in Crimea is 
adversely affected by the presence of Russian military units. 
In the opinion of some deputies, talks should be held with the 
Russian president about the withdrawal of Russian military 
formations, ships, and associations of the Black Sea Fleet 
beyond Ukrainian borders. However, the Ukrainian president does 
not share this point of view. He believes that "this issue 
cannot be approached from this angle". This would be wrong above 
all from a strategic point of view, he said. Ukraine cannot 
afford to deprive Russia of the possibility of having its own 
fleet in the Black Sea, he said. 
  History determined that Ukraine and Russia must be friends, 
live in peace with each other, and have relations of equal 
partnership, he said. The question of the fleet is an "issue 
between Ukraine and Russia," Leonid Kravchuk stressed. And it 
must be resolved gradually without making the situation worse. 
  Some parliamentarians believe that in many respects the 
Crimean issue has arisen because socio-economic problems on the 
peninsula remain unresolved. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-38770 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov106_e_94007" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-106 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  1 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Crimean Adviser Says `Civil Readiness' in Effect </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Crimean Adviser Says `Civil Readiness' in Effect </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0106132994 Moscow RIA in English 0935 GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0106132994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow RIA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, June 1, RIA -- "Morally the people of the 
Crimea are ready for any situation that may develop on the 
peninsula," the Crimean president's military adviser Petr 
Chernyatevich declared in conversation over the telephone with a 
RIA correspondent. A plenary session of the Supreme Soviet of 
the Crimea is opening today to discuss questions relating to the 
present situation. The reaction of the Crimean parliamentarians 
will depend on what decisions the Ukrainian Supreme Soviet 
passes today, believes Chernyatevich. 
  The Crimeans hold a wait-and-see position which can be 
described as the state of civil readiness, according to 
Chernyatevich. He expressed the confidence that the people 
would allow nobody to violate its Constitution. "Kiev must 
reckon with the fact that we have a nationally elected president 
and a nationally elected Supreme Soviet, and the will of the 
people is something that one has to reckon with," said the 
Crimean president's adviser. 
  Right today Petr Chernyatevich intends to meet with the 
commander of the Ukrainian National Guard, Colonel Aleksandr 
Kostyukov in order to find out the reasons and aims of the 
continuing movements of the units subordinate to him. 

</TEXT>

