<H3> <TI>   Navy Men Protest Base Transition to Ukraine Navy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Navy Men Protest Base Transition to Ukraine Navy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0106161094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1421 GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0106161094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [by ITAR-TASS correspondent Vladimir Gondusov] </F>
  [Text] Sevastopol June 1 TASS -- Naval officers and sailors 
serving at the Black Sea Fleet base in the Crimean settlement of 
Donuzlava filed a protest today against the planned transition 
of the base to the Ukrainian Navy. 
  The written protest was handed over to Admiral Feliks 
Gromov, 
commander-in-chief of the Russian Navy, who is now on an 
inspection tour in the Crimea. 
  TASS has learnt that according to the document, over seven 
thousand naval officers and sailors, servicemen of the base's 
garrison, as well as their families will find themselves without 
means of subsistence and will have to leave their homes looking 
for new jobs and housing in case the base in Donuzlava is put 
under the Ukrainian command. Moreover, the protesters are sure 
the base and the settlment will inevitably fall into decay. 
  During the Moscow talks on the Black Sea Fleet's division 
between Russia and Ukraine, the Donuzlava base was named among 
possible locations of the Ukrainan share of the disputed fleet. 

</TEXT>

