<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parliamentary Delegation Leaves for Crimea </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Parliamentary Delegation Leaves for Crimea </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0206113594 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1111 GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0206113594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondents Viktor Demidenko and </F>
Mikhail Melnik] 
  [Text] Kiev 2 June TASS -- A Ukrainian parliamentary 
delegation left today for the Crimea in a bid to settle the 
dispute with this semi-autonomous republic over its latest 
decrees, which are regarded by Kiev as the first step towards 
secession. 
  "In any case, our delegation must spare no efforts in order 
to put an end to all the current negative processes in the 
Crimea. We will do our best to settle all the problems in a 
civilized manner," delegation head Vladimir Butkevich told TASS 
before departure. 
  According to the lawmaker, the delegation has received 
"broad 
powers to conduct negotiations on the whole range of disputed 
problems, including economic and juridical ones, as well as 
problems of security." 
  Butkevich stressed that the delegation will act in 
compliance 
with a parliamentary resolution stipulating that the Crimea's 
decision to reinstate the 1992 constitution was illegal and 
contradicted the laws of Ukraine. 
  The parliament asked President Kravchuk to draw up before 6 
June a list of measures which state power bodies could use 
against the Crimea in case the republic violate's the country's 
Constitution. 

</TEXT>

